    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Is Alcohol the Culprit in Violence?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Dr Lorraine Robertson letter hails Caroline Knapp's June 21 article; holds alcohol spurs violence by unleashing rage</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Drunk and Out of Control'' Op-Ed, June 21):</p>
        <p>Caroline Knapp takes a courageous stand, calling to our attention the role that alcohol has played in the assault in Central Park and in other violent incidents. Because of the ubiquitous nature of alcoholism, too many people try to disguise the problem by putting another face on it. People would rather believe anything else, even that they were mentally ill, rather than face that they or a loved one was alcoholic.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Drunk and Out of Control'' Op-Ed, June 21):</p>
        <p>Caroline Knapp takes a courageous stand, calling to our attention the role that alcohol has played in the assault in Central Park and in other violent incidents. Because of the ubiquitous nature of alcoholism, too many people try to disguise the problem by putting another face on it. People would rather believe anything else, even that they were mentally ill, rather than face that they or a loved one was alcoholic.</p>
        <p>She is also correct in describing the rage that commonly accompanies alcohol use. Many a convict is sitting in a jail today for a crime he committed under the influence of alcohol and of which he has no recall.</p>
        <p>Ms. Knapp says ''alcohol unleashes ugliness and aggression and rage.'' After 20 years of treating alcoholics and following many of them through prolonged sobriety, I realized that alcohol itself was the demon. Most often, when the alcohol is taken out of the picture, the rage and aggression disappear.</p>
        <p>LORRAINE ROBERTSON, M.D.  Mountain Lakes, N.J., June 21, 2000</p>
      </block>
